create_quiz('Secondary Technical Drawing', 'Secondary Technical Drawing — Final Assessment',
'Technical drawing is the language of engineering and construction. This assessment covers the principles of accurate technical illustration.',
25, [
('What is the purpose of technical drawing?', 'multiple_choice',
'Technical drawing (also called engineering drawing or drafting) communicates precise information about objects — their shape, size, material and how they are made — in a standardised format that any trained person anywhere in the world can interpret. A carpenter, engineer or architect can read a technical drawing and construct exactly what the designer intended, without the designer being present. It is the universal language of design and manufacturing.',
[('To make buildings and machines look attractive before they are built', False), ('To communicate precise information about shape, size and construction in a standardised format', True), ('To produce artistic illustrations of engineering projects', False), ('To provide a rough guide for construction that workers can interpret freely', False)]),
('What is an orthographic projection?', 'multiple_choice',
'Orthographic projection shows a 3D object as a series of 2D flat views from different directions — typically front, side and top (plan) views. Each view shows the true shape and dimensions of what can be seen from that direction. First angle projection (used in UK, Africa, most of the world) places the view on the far side of the object. Third angle projection (used in USA) places the view on the near side. The views together give complete information about the object.',
[('A single perspective drawing showing depth and three dimensions', False), ('A series of flat 2D views (front, side, top) showing the true shape from each direction', True), ('A drawing using a special projector to trace objects on paper', False), ('A drawing showing how an object would look from directly above only', False)]),
('What is the scale 1:50 and what does it mean?', 'multiple_choice',
'Scale 1:50 means every 1 unit on the drawing represents 50 units in reality. A room that is 5 metres wide would be drawn as 100mm (10cm) wide. Scale allows large objects (buildings, machines) to be drawn on standard paper sizes while maintaining accurate proportions. Common scales: 1:1 (full size), 1:2 (half size), 1:10, 1:20, 1:50, 1:100 (building plans). To find the real measurement: multiply drawing measurement by the scale factor (50).',
[('The drawing is 50 times larger than the actual object', False), ('Every 1 unit on paper represents 50 units in reality — the object is 50 times larger than drawn', True), ('The drawing was made 50 days before the object was constructed', False), ('50% of the object is shown in the drawing', False)]),
('What instruments are used for technical drawing?', 'multiple_choice',
'Technical drawing instruments: Drawing board and T-square (for horizontal lines), Set squares (45° and 30°/60° — for vertical and angular lines), Compass (for circles and arcs), Pencils (H grades for construction lines — light; HB or B for final lines — darker), Protractor (for measuring angles), Scale rule (for measuring with different scales), French curves or flexi-curves (for irregular curves). Each instrument serves a specific purpose. Accurate drawing requires clean, sharp instruments.',
[('A camera and photo editing software to create technical images', False), ('Drawing board, T-square, set squares, compass, scale rule and graded pencils', True), ('A computer with CAD software is the only tool needed for technical drawing', False), ('Only a ruler and pencil are needed — other instruments are optional', False)]),
('What is isometric drawing?', 'multiple_choice',
'Isometric drawing shows a 3D object on a flat surface using three axes at 120° to each other (typically vertical, and two others at 30° to the horizontal). It gives a realistic 3D impression while maintaining true proportions on all three axes — unlike perspective drawing where far dimensions appear smaller. Isometric drawings are commonly used in technical manuals, furniture assembly instructions and engineering presentations where a 3D view is needed with accurate proportions.',
[('A drawing of objects as seen by the human eye with perspective foreshortening', False), ('A 3D representation using three axes at 120° — showing realistic shape without perspective distortion', True), ('A drawing showing the internal structure by cutting through an object', False), ('A drawing showing only the front face of an object in full detail', False)]),
('What does a hidden line (dashed line) represent in a technical drawing?', 'multiple_choice',
'In technical drawing, hidden lines are shown as dashed lines (short equal dashes). They represent edges or features that exist behind a surface and cannot be directly seen from the viewing direction. For example, a hole drilled through a block would appear as dashed lines on the front view showing the hidden far edge. Understanding hidden lines is essential for reading and interpreting technical drawings correctly — they reveal what is happening inside or behind the visible surfaces.',
[('Lines that the draughtsman has decided to remove from the final drawing', False), ('Features hidden behind a surface that cannot be directly seen from the viewing direction', True), ('Lines that indicate where cuts should be made during construction', False), ('Alternative positions that the object could be placed in', False)]),
('What is a section view in technical drawing?', 'multiple_choice',
'A section view (cross-section) shows what an object looks like when it is cut through at a specific plane. It reveals internal features — holes, cavities, wall thickness — that cannot be seen in standard views. The cutting plane is shown on another view as a line with arrows indicating viewing direction. Cross-hatching (diagonal lines) is used to show the material that has been "cut through." Sections are essential for complex mechanical parts and building drawings.',
[('A view showing a very small section of a larger drawing at a larger scale', False), ('A view showing the internal structure by imagining the object cut through at a specific plane', True), ('A separate drawing showing only the dimensions without the object shape', False), ('A view showing the object from a section of society\'s perspective for social impact assessment', False)]),
('What is the purpose of dimensioning a technical drawing?', 'multiple_choice',
'Dimensions on a technical drawing communicate the exact sizes of all features — lengths, widths, heights, radii, angles and positions of holes or features. Without dimensions, a drawing cannot be used to construct anything — the maker would not know the actual sizes. Dimensions must: use the same units throughout (mm is standard in most countries), be clear and unambiguous, be placed outside the object outline, and use extension lines, dimension lines and arrowheads correctly.',
[('To make the drawing look complete and professionally finished', False), ('To communicate the exact sizes of all features so the object can be constructed accurately', True), ('To indicate which dimensions can be estimated and which must be exact', False), ('To show what the drawing is about without needing to read the title block', False)]),
('What is Computer Aided Design (CAD)?', 'multiple_choice',
'CAD software (like AutoCAD, SolidWorks, FreeCAD) allows technical drawings to be created on a computer rather than on paper. Advantages: drawings can be edited easily (no erasing), can be scaled instantly, 3D models can be created and rotated, dimensions update automatically, drawings can be shared electronically, and manufacturing machines can be directly controlled by CAD data (CAD/CAM). CAD has largely replaced manual drafting in professional engineering and architecture.',
[('Computer Added Design — software that suggests design improvements automatically', False), ('Software for creating precise technical drawings on a computer, replacing manual drafting', True), ('A camera system that digitises paper drawings into computer files', False), ('Computer Animated Drawing — for creating moving images of engineering designs', False)]),
('What does the title block of a technical drawing contain?', 'multiple_choice',
'The title block, placed in the bottom right corner of a technical drawing, contains essential information: title/name of the drawing, drawing number, scale, date drawn, name of draughtsman, name of company or institution, revision history (changes made and when), units used, projection method (first or third angle), and sheet number. Without a title block, the drawing cannot be properly identified, filed or used in a professional context.',
[('Only the title of what is being drawn', False), ('Title, drawing number, scale, date, draughtsman, company, revision history and projection method', True), ('The materials list for the construction of the object drawn', False), ('A summary of all dimensions used in the drawing', False)]),
])

